      "\n  have h₁ : {n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n < φ n}.HasDensity 1 := by\n    have h₂ : {n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n < φ n} = {n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n < φ n} := rfl\n    rw [h₂]\n    have h₃ : {n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n < φ n}.HasDensity 1 := by\n      -- Use the fact that the set of n where φ(n) > φ(n - φ(n)) has density 1\n      -- and the fact that f(n) = o(n) to show that the set {n | φ(n - φ(n)) + f(n) < φ(n)}\n      -- has density 1.\n      have h₄ : {n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n < φ n}.HasDensity 1 := by\n        -- Use the fact that the set of n where φ(n) > φ(n - φ(n)) has density 1\n        -- and the fact that f(n) = o(n) to show that the set {n | φ(n - φ(n)) + f(n) < φ(n)}\n        -- has density 1.\n        have h₅ : {n : ℕ | φ n > φ (n - φ n)}.HasDensity 1 := by\n          -- This is given by the first problem (Erdős Problem 1064)\n          exact by\n            -- Use the fact that the set of n where φ(n) > φ(n - φ(n)) has density 1\n            -- (as given by Erdős Problem 1064)\n            exact\n              by\n                have h₅₁ : {n : ℕ | φ n > φ (n - φ n)}.HasDensity 1 := by sorry\n                exact h₅₁\n        -- Use the fact that f(n) = o(n) to show that for almost all n, f(n) < φ(n)\n        -- and thus φ(n - φ(n)) + f(n) < φ(n) if φ(n) > φ(n - φ(n))\n        have h₆ : {n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n < φ n}.HasDensity 1 := by\n          -- Use the fact that f(n) = o(n) to show that for almost all n, f(n) < φ(n)\n          -- and thus φ(n - φ(n)) + f(n) < φ(n) if φ(n) > φ(n - φ(n))\n          exact by\n            have h₆₁ : {n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n < φ n}.HasDensity 1 := by sorry\n            exact h₆₁\n        exact h₆\n      exact h₄\n    exact h₃\n  exact h₁",
      "another approach: \n\nThe set of n where φ(n) < n/2 is the same as the set where there exists a prime p such that p² divides n (see [this MSE post](https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/1785742/for-which-n-is-varphin-geq-n-2)). So the density of the set where φ(n) < n/2 is 0 because it is contained in the set of n divisible by p² for some prime p, and the sum over p of 1/p² is < 1. \n\nThus, for almost all n, φ(n) ≥ n/2. \n\nThen, for such n, φ(n - φ(n)) ≤ n - φ(n) ≤ n - n/2 = n/2, because φ(n - φ(n)) ≤ n - φ(n). \n\nBut also, f(n) = o(n), so for large n, f(n) < n/2. \n\nBut we want φ(n - φ(n)) + f(n) < φ(n). \n\nIn this case, φ(n - φ(n)) + f(n) < n/2 + n/2 = n. \n\nBut φ(n) ≥ n/2, so φ(n - φ(n)) + f(n) < 2 φ(n), which is not enough. \n\nHowever, perhaps we can use that φ(n - φ(n)) ≤ n - φ(n), so φ(n - φ(n)) + f(n) ≤ n - φ(n) + f(n), and we want n - φ(n) + f(n) < φ(n), i.e., n + f(n) < 2 φ(n).\n\nBut since φ(n) ≥ n/2, we have 2φ(n) ≥ n, and f(n) = o(n), so for large n, f(n) < (2φ(n) - n). \n\nBut 2φ(n) - n ≥ 0 (as φ(n) ≥ n/2), and we would need to ensure that 2φ(n) - n > f(n). \n\nBut if φ(n) = (1 - ε) n (e.g., if n is prime, φ(n) = n - 1), then 2φ(n) - n = (1 - 2ε) n, but if ε is very small, this is ~ n, and since f(n) = o(n), we are fine. \n\nBut if φ(n) ≈ n/2, 2φ(n) - n ≈ 0. \n\nHowever, in the case when φ(n) ≈ n/2, we have φ(n - φ(n)) ≤ n - φ(n) ≈ n/2, and f(n) = o(n), but φ(n) ≈ n/2. \n\nBut then φ(n - φ(n)) + f(n) ≈ n/2 + o(n) < n/2 is false. \n\nHmm, this seems problematic. \n\nWait no, actually: \n\nIf φ(n) ≈ n/2, then n/2 + o(n) < n/2 is false. \n\nBut we have φ(n - φ(n)) ≤ n - φ(n) ≈ n/2, so φ(n - φ(n)) + f(n) ≤ n/2 + o(n), and we want this < φ(n) ≈ n/2. \n\nBut n/2 + o(n) < n/2 is false, because o(n) could be positive. \n\nHowever, perhaps in reality, when φ(n) ≈ n/2, φ(n - φ(n)) is actually much smaller. \n\nFor example, take n = 2^k. Then φ(n) = 2^{k-1} = n/2. \n\nn - φ(n) = 2^{k-1}. \n\nφ(n - φ(n)) = 2^{k-2} =",
      "when `n ∈ D`, `φ(n) ≥ 2` for `n ≥ 4`, because if `n ≥ 4` and `φ(n) = 1`, then `n = 2, 3`, and for `n = 3`, `φ(3) = 2`, not `1`, and `n = 2`, `φ(2) = 1`, `n - φ(n) = 1`, `φ(1) = 1`, so `φ(2) = φ(1)` and `2 ∉ D`. \n\nThus, for `n ∈ D`, `n ≥ 3` and `φ(n) ≥ 2` except for `n = 2`, which is not in `D`.\n\nThus, for `n ∈ D`, `φ(n) ≥ 2`, and `n - φ(n) < n`, so perhaps `φ(n - φ(n)) ≤ n - φ(n)`.\n\nHmm, no, `φ(6) = 2`, `6 - φ(6) = 4`, `φ(4) = 2 ≤ 4`, yes. \n\nFor `n = 7`, `φ(7) = 6`, `n - φ(n) = 1`, `φ(1) = 1 ≤ 1`, yes.\n\nBut for `n = 8`, `φ(8) = 4`, `n - φ(n) = 4`, `φ(4) = 2 ≤ 4`. \n\nHmm, so in general, for `m ≥ 1`, `φ(m) ≤ m`.\n\nThus, for `n ∈ D`, `φ(n - φ(n)) ≤ n - φ(n)`, because `n - φ(n) ≥ 1` for `n ≥ 2`, and if `n = 1`, `n - φ(n) = 0` but `φ(0)` is not defined (but in Lean `φ(0) = 0`, so `φ(1 - φ(1)) = φ(1 - 1) = φ(0) =",
      "in reality, if we let `C = {n : ϕ(n - ϕ(n)) + f(n) ≥ ϕ(n)}`, then `C ⊆ A ∪ B`, because if `n ∉ A`, then `ϕ(n - ϕ(n)) < ϕ(n)`; then `ϕ(n - ϕ(n)) + f(n) ≥ ϕ(n)` would imply `f(n) ≥ ϕ(n) - ϕ(n - ϕ(n))`. But since `ϕ(n) - ϕ(n - ϕ(n)) > 0`, perhaps we can't directly deduce `f(n) ≥ ϕ(n)` unless we have some bounds.\n\nHowever, I think we can use the following:\n\nActually, we know that for any `f(n) = o(n)`, the set `{n : f(n) ≥ n / 2}` has density 0 (since for large enough `n`, `f(n) < n / 2`).\n\nAlso, it is known that `ϕ(n) ≥ n / 2` for infinitely many `n` (e.g., all odd `n`). \n\nBut to get that `ϕ(n) > f(n)` for almost all `n`, we could use that `ϕ(n) > n / e^γ log log n` for infinitely many `n` (but that's complicated). \n\nAlternatively, perhaps for all `n` that are `1 mod 2`, `ϕ(n) ≥ √n`, because for `n` odd, if `n` is a prime, then `ϕ(n) = n - 1 ≥ √n` for `n ≥ 3`; if `n = p^k`, then `ϕ(n) = p^k - p^{k-1} ≈ p^k`, etc. \n\nBut this is too involved.\n\n#### Simpler Approach\nActually, perhaps we can instead use that `Erdos1064` gives that the set `{n : ϕ(n) > ϕ(n - ϕ(n))}` has density 1, so its complement `A = {n : ϕ(n) ≤ ϕ(n - ϕ(n))}` has density 0, and then try to show that `{n : ϕ(n - ϕ(n)) + f(n) ≥ ϕ(n)} ⊆ A ∪ {n : f(n) ≥ something}` and that the latter set also has density 0. \n\nBut for `n ∉ A`, we have `ϕ(n - ϕ(n)) < ϕ(n)`, so `ϕ(n - ϕ(n)) + f(n) < ϕ(n) + f(n)`. We need to ensure that for almost all `n`, `f(n) < ϕ(n) - ϕ(n - ϕ(n))`. However, `ϕ(n) - ϕ(n - ϕ(n))` could be very small (e.g., if `n = 2`, `ϕ(2) = 1`, `n - ϕ(n) = 1`, `ϕ(1) = 1`, then `ϕ(n) - ϕ(n - ϕ(n)) = 0`).\n\nHmm, this seems not to work.\n\nBut if instead we could prove that for almost all `n`, we have `ϕ(n) - ϕ(n - ϕ(n)) > 1`, then since `f(n)` is an integer, we would have `ϕ(n - ϕ(n)) + 1 ≤ ϕ(n)`, so that `ϕ(n - ϕ(n)) + f(n) < ϕ(n)` would follow if `f(n) = 0`. But `f(n)` is arbitrary and positive. This doesn't help. \n\n#### Another Idea: Using Large Primes\n1. We know that `ϕ(p) = p - 1`, and for `n = p`, `n - ϕ(n) = 1`, so `ϕ(n - ϕ(n)) = 1`, and `ϕ(n) = p - 1`. Thus `ϕ(n - ϕ(n)) + f(n) = 1 + f(p)`, and `ϕ(n) = p - 1`. The inequality becomes `1 + f(p) < p - 1`, or `f(p) < p - 2`. But since `f(p) = o(p)`, for sufficiently large `p`, `f(p) < p - 2`. The set of primes has density 0, but perhaps we can use that the set of numbers of the form `p + k` for small `k` is dense? \n\nBut it is unclear. \n\n#### Using the First Lean Theorem\nAlternatively",
      "\n  have h₁ : {n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n < φ n}.HasDensity 1 := by\n    have h₂ : Set.Finite {n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n ≥ φ n} := by\n      classical\n      -- Prove that the set is finite by showing it is bounded\n      have h₃ : ∃ (N : ℕ), ∀ (n : ℕ), n ∈ {n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n ≥ φ n} → n ≤ N := by\n        use 0\n        intro n hn\n        have h₄ : φ (n - φ n) + f n ≥ φ n := by simpa using hn\n        have h₅ : n = 0 := by\n          by_contra h\n          have h₆ : n ≥ 1 := by\n            omega\n          have h₇ : φ n ≥ 1 := by\n            apply Nat.succ_le_of_lt\n            apply Nat.totient_pos.mpr\n            omega\n          have h₈ : n - φ n < n := by\n            have h₉ : φ n ≥ 1 := by\n              apply Nat.succ_le_of_lt\n              apply Nat.totient_pos.mpr\n              omega\n            have h₁₀ : φ n ≤ n := by\n              apply Nat.totient_le\n            omega\n          have h₉ : φ (n - φ n) ≤ n - φ n := by\n            apply Nat.totient_le\n          have h₁₀ : φ (n - φ n) + f n < φ n + f n := by\n            have h₁₁ : φ (n - φ n) ≤ n - φ n := by\n              apply Nat.totient_le\n            have h₁₂ : n - φ n < n := by\n              have h₁₃ : φ n ≥ 1 := by\n                apply Nat.succ_le_of_lt\n                apply Nat.totient_pos.mpr\n                omega\n              omega\n            have h₁₃ : φ (n - φ n) < n := by\n              omega\n            have h₁₄ : φ (n - φ n) < φ n + f n := by\n              have h₁₅ : φ n ≥ 1 := by\n                apply Nat.succ_le_of_lt\n                apply Nat.totient_pos.mpr\n                omega\n              have h₁₆ : f n ≥ 0 := by\n                exact Nat.zero_le (f n)\n              nlinarith [h₉]\n            omega\n          have h₁₁ : φ n + f n ≤ φ (n - φ n) + f n := by\n            omega\n          omega\n        simp_all\n      obtain ⟨N, hN⟩ := h₃\n      -- Use the bound to show that the set is finite\n      have h₄ : {n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n ≥ φ n} ⊆ Set.Iic N := by\n        intro n hn\n        have h₅ : n ≤ N := hN n hn\n        exact h₅\n      exact Set.Finite.subset (Set.finite_Iic N) h₄\n    -- Use the fact that the complement is finite to deduce the density is 1\n    have h₃ : {n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n < φ n}.HasDensity 1 := by\n      have h₄ : {n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n < φ n} = {n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n < φ n} := rfl\n      rw [h₄]\n      have h₅ : ({n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n < φ n} : Set ℕ) = (Set.univ : Set ℕ) \\ {n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n ≥ φ n} := by\n        ext n\n        simp [not_le]\n        <;>\n        (try omega) <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            by_cases h : φ (n - φ n) + f n < φ n <;>\n            simp_all [Nat.lt_succ_iff]\n            <;>\n            omega\n          })\n        <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            by_cases h : φ (n - φ n) + f n ≥ φ n <;>\n            simp_all [Nat.lt_succ_iff]\n            <;>\n            omega\n          })\n      rw [h₅]\n      -- Since the complement is finite, the set has density 1\n      have h₆ : ({n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n ≥ φ n} : Set ℕ).Finite := h₂\n      have h₇ : ((Set.univ : Set ℕ) \\ {n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n ≥ φ n}).HasDensity 1 := by\n        -- Use the fact that the complement is finite to deduce the density is 1\n        have h₈ : ({n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n ≥ φ n} : Set ℕ).Finite := h₂\n        have h₉ : ((Set.univ : Set ℕ) \\ {n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n ≥ φ n}).HasDensity 1 := by\n          -- Use the fact that the complement is finite to deduce the density is 1\n          have h₁₀ : (Set.univ : Set ℕ).HasDensity 1 := by\n            -- The density of the entire space is 1\n            simpa using (hasDensity_univ : (Set.univ : Set ℕ).HasDensity 1)\n          -- Use the fact that the complement is finite to deduce the density is 1\n          have h₁₁ : (((Set.univ : Set ℕ) \\ {n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n ≥ φ n} : Set ℕ)).HasDensity 1 := by\n            apply h₁₀.diff_null\n            -- The complement has density 0 because it is finite\n            have h₁₂ : ({n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n ≥ φ n} : Set ℕ).Finite := h₂\n            have h₁₃ : ({n : ℕ | φ (n - φ n) + f n ≥ φ n} : Set ℕ).HasDensity 0 := by\n              -- A finite set has density 0\n              exact (hasDensity_finite_to_zero _)\n            simpa using h₁₃\n          exact h₁₁\n        exact h₉\n      exact h₇\n    exact h₃\n  exact h₁",
